<subSubSection id="C354656F6750FFD5608EF82D526FFDCC" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="273" pageId="8" pageNumber="269" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF136E46750FFD5608EF82D526FFDCC" blockId="8.[151,1437,1392,2030]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1437,153,539]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="273" pageId="8" pageNumber="269">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66750FFD1608EF82D576DF871" box="[199,305,1932,1958]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="269">Remarks.</emphasis>
Although 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676750FFD161E1F82D5460F872" authorityName="Suarez" authorityYear="1970" box="[424,572,1932,1958]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Dasymutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66750FFD161E1F82D5460F872" box="[424,572,1932,1958]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="269">Q. peruviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females are consistent in most aspects with the general morphological trends of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676750FFD16095F8115725F81D" authorityName="Brothers &amp; Lelej" authorityYear="2017" box="[220,377,1968,1994]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Dasymutillini">Dasymutillini</taxonomicName>
, the clypeus and mandibles of the males are even more distorted than the other known 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676750FFD1657BF81153C0F81D" authority="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira, 2019" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" box="[1330,1436,1968,1994]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66750FFD1657BF81153C0F81D" box="[1330,1436,1968,1994]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="269">Quwitilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676750FFD160AEF87557D3F839" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[231,399,2004,2030]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blattoserica">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66750FFD160AEF87557D3F839" box="[231,399,2004,2030]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="269">Q. blattoserica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is clear, however that these belong to the newly described genus based on their genitalia, which only differs from those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD561B4FF3854FDFF64" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[509,673,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blattoserica">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD561B4FF3854FDFF64" box="[509,673,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. blattoserica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the distribution of the paramere ventral setae. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B156754FFD564F2FF385309FF64" author="Suarez, F. J." box="[1211,1365,153,179]" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" pagination="169 - 188" refId="ref10283" refString="Suarez, F. J. (1970) Datos sobre Mutilidos neotropicales VII. Algunas especies del Peru representadas en las colecciones del Museo de Historia Natural de Basilea (Suiza). Archivos del Instituto de Aclimataccion de Almeria, 15, 169 - 188." type="journal article" year="1970">Suárez (1970)</bibRefCitation>
raised the possibility of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD5611EFF1C57BBFF00" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Suarez" baseAuthorityYear="1970" box="[343,487,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD5611EFF1C57BBFF00" box="[343,487,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. peruviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being the male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD562FFFF1C5534FF00" box="[694,872,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Dasymutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="homochroma">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD562FFFF1C5534FF00" box="[694,872,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. homochroma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and discarded the hypothesis based on the fact that while both sexes of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD56133FF40547CFF2C" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[378,544,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blattoserica">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD56133FF40547CFF2C" box="[378,544,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. blattoserica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had coloration similarities, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD56310FF4055B0FF2C" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Suarez" baseAuthorityYear="1970" box="[857,1004,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD56310FF4055B0FF2C" box="[857,1004,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. peruviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD5646CFF405284FF2C" box="[1061,1240,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Dasymutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="homochroma">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD5646CFF405284FF2C" box="[1061,1240,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. homochroma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were remarkably different. We consider that having both species collected in the same date and place in an area where diurnal species of velvet-ant are uncommon, and their clear similarities with 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD56345FE8855F3FE94" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[780,943,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blattoserica">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD56345FE8855F3FE94" box="[780,943,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. blattoserica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sufficient evidence for the sex association proposed here. As previously mentioned, the female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD56349FEEC55CEFEB0" authorityName="Bartholomay &amp; Williams &amp; Cambra &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Suarez" baseAuthorityYear="1970" box="[768,914,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Quwitilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD56349FEEC55CEFEB0" box="[768,914,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Q. peruviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to belong to a distinct color syndrome with other species west of the Andes. The male, however, remarkably approaches the color patterns observed in two other 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD5609CFE34571BFE78" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[213,327,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mutillidae</taxonomicName>
species occurring west of the Andes: 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD56292FE3452BAFE78" authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1874" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[731,1254,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD56292FE345255FE78" box="[731,1033,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Traumatomutilla vitelligera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B156754FFD5645FFE345281FE78" author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[1046,1245,405,431]" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" pagination="41 - 77" refId="ref9443" refString="Gerstaecker, A. (1874) Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte, 40, 41 - 77 + 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD56551FE3657E6FE03" authority="(Andre, 1906)" authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1906" baseAuthorityName="Andre" baseAuthorityYear="1906" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Hoplomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculifrons">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD56551FE3653C0FE78" box="[1304,1436,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Hoplomutilla</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD560DEFE185745FE04" box="[151,281,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">maculifrons</emphasis>
(André, 1906)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13752A616754FFD56181FE185414FE04" box="[456,584,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–40" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1940,1965]" captionTargetBox="[271,1316,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[271,1316,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 38–40. 38. Quwitilla peruviana (Suárez, 1970), ♂, holotype; 39. Hoplomutilla maculifrons (André, 1906); 40. Traumatomutilla vitelligera (Gerstaecker, 1874)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3255433/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Figs 38–40</figureCitation>
). This could be an example of Dual Sex-limited Mimicry, which was first proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B156754FFD56148FE7C57D2FE20" author="Evans, H. E." box="[257,398,477,503]" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" pagination="1 - 22" refId="ref9354" refString="Evans, H. E. (1968) Studies on Neotropical Pompilidae (Hymenoptera), IV. Examples of Dual Sex-Limited Mimicry in Chirodamus. Psyche, 75, 1 - 22. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 1968 / 76089" type="journal article" year="1968">Evans (1968</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B156754FFD561D3FE7C578EFE2F" author="Evans, H. E." box="[410,466,477,504]" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" pagination="18 - 28" refId="ref9401" refString="Evans, H. E. (1969) Studies on Neotropical Pompilidae (Hymenoptera), V. Austrochares Banks. Psyche, 76, 18 - 28. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 1969 / 50293" type="journal article" year="1969">1969</bibRefCitation>
) in Neotropical pompilids, but has also been observed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D676754FFD56407FE7C53C5FE20" authority="(Williams, 2012)" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="Williams" baseAuthorityYear="2012" box="[1102,1433,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Dasymutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEAF66754FFD56407FE7C5288FE20" box="[1102,1236,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="273">Dasymutilla</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B156754FFD564ABFE7C53CDFE20" author="Williams, K. A." box="[1250,1425,477,503]" pageId="12" pageNumber="273" refId="ref10406" refString="Williams, K. A. (2012) Systematics of Mutillidae (Hymenoptera) with special emphasis on Dasymutilla and their alles. All Graduate Theses and Dissertations. Paper 1200. Utah State Univeristy Press, Logan, Utah, 327 pp. Available from: http: // digitalcommons. usu. edu / etd / 1200 / (Las accessed November 2018)" type="book" year="2012">Williams, 2012</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Further studies into the mimetic syndromes of South American mutillids are needed.
</paragraph>
